**bachelorette spoiler alert**
.
.
Here to remind all of us (myself very much included) to be careful with throwing around words like “toxic” and “gaslighting” and “narcissism” so easily. 
.
.
I was really saddened watching this week’ episode of The Bachelorette.
I hope we can remember that the conflict we witnessed Greg and Katie go through publicly was something that can easily happen for many of us behind closed doors when we become deeply emotionally dis-regulated. 
I have been in (both) of their shoes at different times in my life.
.
.
I have also worked with (many) couples who have struggled immensely to connect with one another and to find the appropriate/attuned way of offering supportive validation during distress. 
That shit is sometimes really damn HARD!!!
.
.
I have seen partners leave and relationships come to an end not because either of them wanted the relationship to end — but because the anxiety within one or both partners simply became intolerable.
.
.
If we are that quick to judge and demonize people for having relational difficulties, where does that leave the rest of us? 
Have gossip columns and social media and reality tv become the modern day battles that took place in Greek colosseums — so that we may project and direct our darkest and most shadowey selves? 
I don’t know.
Social media is really strange sometimes.
.
.
I’m hoping this video speaks to the rest of what my heart and mind was trying to convey here.
Please keep your comments respectful on this video — no character bashing whatsoever will be tolerated.
.
.
P.S. I refer to bids a few times in this video. A “bid” is a term coined by @gottmaninstitute and bids are the gestures between a couple that signal a need for attention. A bid can be a request for more connection, a request for vulnerability or reassurance, and so much more!

✨Supportive Offers✨
.
.
💫For support on dating, my 12-week online program Empowered Dating offers attachment-based wisdom to help you identify and express your needs with more clarity, and help you relate to others with more confidence and attunement. 
.
.
💫For boundaries support, my 6-week Boundaries Program created with my husband @bryanreevesinsight teaches you how to identify what your core boundary needs are and guides you to communicate them in respectful and relationally sensitive ways. This program has a ton of practical scripts included in it to support you to develop your own language-ing for boundaries. 
.
.
💫For couples support, my 90-day Conflict to Connection program teaches you 6 research based relationship skills to help you and your partner understand one another more intimately so that you can repair and return to connection more quickly.
.
.
All of these programs are educational and not meant to be used in replacement of therapy or professional support. 
Many people have shared with me that the teachings in the programs have been an amazing complimentary guide to use along with their personal or couples counseling to help deepen their work.
.
.
The links for all 3 programs can be found in my bio 💙🌻✨

Question: What if my partner wants to take a week of space?
.
.
Every couple has to negotiate the amount of connection and space that will exist in their relationship. 
The only people that can decide what will work work them are the people in it. 
We have to keep our moral judgments of our these conversations and support couples to create what works for them. 
Some couples love having more closeness while others enjoy having more time apart.
.
.
How those needs for closeness or space are negotiated matters a lot. 
Are both people being considered in the decisions?
Is one partner bending to accommodate the other more often that the other partner?
Are both partners making some adjustments to support the couple as a unit?
How is power in the relationship being distributed - is the power shared?
.
.
Questions for Couples:
✨ How do you navigate conversations that require compromise?
✨ How do you know when you are meeting in the middle-ish? 
*(I say middle-ish because I don’t believe there is such a thing as a perfect middle for anything).

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Silvy Khoucasian on August 07, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'You are allowed to have needs. You are allowed to assess and reflect on whether a person's boundaries work for you. You are allowed to question relationships and people that are committed to relating in one-sided ways. You are allowed to protect yourself from people who are completely unwilling to compromise or hear your side of things. You are allowed to set boundaries with people who have deeply disconnecting and rigid boundaries. Silvy Khoucasian'.

node.text:
Some people are extremely rigid in the way they hold and express their boundaries. 
Some people use boundaries as a way to self-protect as a way to avoid having to feel into their vulnerabilities.
.
. 
With all of that said, we still don’t get to decide what a persons boundaries are, even if those boundaries might be walls.
People are allowed to be as rigid or closed off as they want to be.
.
.
What we can however do is reflect on whether a person’s relational boundaries create enough space and possibility for intimacy and connection to take place. 
We get to decide if our relational needs are being met (enough) and we aren’t stuck chasing a person who doesn’t want to be caught.
.
.
Some people who have really strong avoidant tendencies can unknowingly use boundaries as a way to prevent too much closeness from happening.
This is not often not an intentional thing.
.
.
Having feedback offered in non-pressuring ways can be vital to recognizing this pattern. 
Having people we trust begin to express their relational needs (while they don’t force us to change our boundary) can sometimes help us learn to soften some of our more rigid ones over time.
.
.
Tread delicately here, because coming up against peoples defenses will most likely trigger some defensiveness.
Expect that. 
See if you can move into that space in a gentle and non-probing way. 
Acknowledge your needs and see if there is room to have a deeper conversation. 
There may not be an opening available.
But you can only find out if you walk towards this space.
.
.
“I really respect your needs and your boundaries with this. I would love to feel closer to you and I’m noticing that this has been getting in the way of me experiencing that with you. Can we explore that together?”
.
.
“I hear your boundary fully and I want you to know that I am not pressuring you to do things differently. I am realizing that I am feeling quite disconnected and would love more quality time together. How can we make this work for both of us?”
.
.
These conversations are rarely easy to have.
And yet they can offer us incredibly vital information regarding the quality of connection that will be available to us.
#coachingwithsilvy

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Silvy Khoucasian on August 06, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Offering positivity and optimism when a person is in profound pain can become deeply hurtful when what they really need is validation and mirroring and understanding and acknowledgement and connection. Silvy Khoucasian'.

node.text:
This post is not meant to bash positivity as a whole or put down any of you that are optimistic by nature and that tend to look for the silver linings.
We need your optimism.
We need your hopefulness.
We need your ability to see the world through your joyful and affirming lens, perhaps right now more than ever.
.
.
However - we do need to take context into consideration - always.
.
.
Love and empathy offered without attuning or ever considering other people’s boundaries can sometimes become intrusive and inappropriate.
Consideration of others without ever considering and expressing your own needs can feed into a deeply imbalanced relating dynamic.
Any quality/offering can become hurtful when it is not contextualized properly to appropriately fit and attune to a particular person or situation.
Any positive gesture that doesn’t make space for flexibility and the ability to shift the approach based on the other person’s actual needs can become deeply disconnecting.
.
.
Even the most well-intended agendas of positivity can become harmful when the person before us in a deep well of pain and is needing support and mirroring and validation.
Positivity can become hurtful when it is is never balanced with the acknowledgment of painful and challenging realities.
.
.
This is a hard one to sit with, I assure you, I know.
In family/cultural systems where pain, sadness, grief/loss were quickly glazed over, it makes perfect sense that we might resort to doing exactly the same to others.
As my therapist often says to me during sessions, “It goes out the same way it goes in Silvy” - that is until we become more conscious and aware of relationally disconnecting and invalidating behaviors.
.
.
P.S. Sometimes people will be tired and may not have the ability to hold our heavier feelings - that is very normal and different than a person who is completely unwilling and unavailable to learn how to do this better/differently. Sometimes people also need more lightness and fun and a break from discussing heavier things. Please be mindful not to take this message on too rigidly or without considering what the other person might need too.
#coachingwithsilvy

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Silvy Khoucasian on August 05, 2021. May be an image of 1 person.

node.text:
I have often been the runner in most of my relationships. 
Facing conflict and speaking my needs out loud never felt fully safe. 
It was easier (and much safer) to focus outward and blame/criticize my partners than it was to express the vulnerabilities that lived within me.
.
.
On top of that, I rarely had the language to actually understand and articulate what was happening inside of me.
I have long been envious of people who could express their needs and feelings with fluidity and ease.
.
.
Looking back, I think many of my past partners would have been able to meet my needs had I been better at expressing them.
It makes me deeply sad to think about the missed opportunities I’ve had.
.
.
When I met my current partner, the runner was still very much alive in me.
The runner is still alive in me now. 
I just have a different relationship with that part of me now. 
I can better understand what it is trying to protect me from. 
I still go to my therapist to process my patterns of avoidance and she helps me understand the root cause and reminds me to consider the various contexts that may be at play.
.
.
With her guidance, I can sit with and question the deeper layers of what is happening inside of me so that I don’t act out on my fears.
I can now better understand my hyper-focus and attempts at creating perfection and safety even when safety exists right before me.
.
.
My partner is also a deeply embracing, grounded, and logical person, and his support and understanding has been without a doubt our saving grace. 
We are also both huge advocates of getting support, and we go to therapy when we need it. 
Couples should never have to feel shame about getting help, although I’m fully aware that our culture is still in the newer stages of busting stigmas around mental health.
.
.
I can’t empathize enough the importance of getting support if you struggle with intense avoidance patterns. 
Our defenses are meant to protect us and help us survive in our environments.
And yet they can also get in the way of love and connection when we don’t learn how to put them in their proper place.
They can sometimes get in the way of the very things we want the most.
~Silvy Khoucasian

node.text:
Being repeatedly vulnerable with someone who is not willing to also take relational risks is not likely going to create a warm and intimate connection.
Being the person who always initiates without ever asking for the other person to initiate back may not likely create a balanced and reciprocal relationship.
Being the only person who takes responsibility during conflict isn’t going to set the stage for us to feel heard and validated ourselves.
.
.
I know I talk a lot about taking responsibility for our side of the street.
I’m a huge advocate of that.
I’m (also) however a huge advocate of assessing and exploring when we might take that too far.
I’m an advocate of speaking out relational imbalances to better assess if the other person wants to lean in and also engage.
I’m an advocate of paying attention to the relational roles we may repeatedly drop into that can block us from the very connection we seek.
.
.
I do believe that most of us do want to show up in our relationships.
We may not always be aware of our lack of effort.
We may not be aware that we haven’t been contributing.
We may need to be gently called forward into this space by the people around us.
.
.
I also want to mention that one person may contribute and offer gifts towards a relationship in ways that are very different than the other person.
You can also create relational balance in that way.
Explore that.
.
.
Explore willingness and desire on both sides.
Explore someone’s longing to meet and create balance with you.
Explore ways to make space for the ebbs and flows of life when contribution and effort may not always be mutually possible.
Explore how you can shift the relational dance without relying on criticism and blame.
See if you can explore these things without minimizing your valid needs and desires.
#coachingwithsilvy
.
.
What comes up for you in this dialogue?
Where do you get stuck?
Where do you tend to take too much responsibility?
Where do you not take enough?
What might empower you to advocate for your needs more?
Where can softening some of your expectations serve you?

**bachelorette spoiler alert**
.
.
Here to remind all of us (myself very much included) to be careful with throwing around words like “toxic” and “gaslighting” and “narcissism” so easily. 
.
.
I was really saddened watching this week’ episode of The Bachelorette.
I hope we can remember that the conflict we witnessed Greg and Katie go through publicly was something that can easily happen for many of us behind closed doors when we become deeply emotionally dis-regulated. 
I have been in (both) of their shoes at different times in my life.
.
.
I have also worked with (many) couples who have struggled immensely to connect with one another and to find the appropriate/attuned way of offering supportive validation during distress. 
That shit is sometimes really damn HARD!!!
.
.
I have seen partners leave and relationships come to an end not because either of them wanted the relationship to end — but because the anxiety within one or both partners simply became intolerable.
.
.
If we are that quick to judge and demonize people for having relational difficulties, where does that leave the rest of us? 
Have gossip columns and social media and reality tv become the modern day battles that took place in Greek colosseums — so that we may project and direct our darkest and most shadowey selves? 
I don’t know.
Social media is really strange sometimes.
.
.
I’m hoping this video speaks to the rest of what my heart and mind was trying to convey here.
Please keep your comments respectful on this video — no character bashing whatsoever will be tolerated.
.
.
P.S. I refer to bids a few times in this video. A “bid” is a term coined by @gottmaninstitute and bids are the gestures between a couple that signal a need for attention. A bid can be a request for more connection, a request for vulnerability or reassurance, and so much more!

node.text:
One layer of boundaries is learning to set protective limits with ourselves and honoring our moment by moment capacity.
We can sometimes protect our capacity by pausing before agreeing to things, strengthening our muscle to say no to experiences we don’t want, or turning down experiences we simply don’t have the bandwidth to engage in.
We can do this by not participating in things that feel harmful or are not aligned with the kind of life we want to live.
.
.
Nourishing boundaries, however, can also be about allowing spaciousness to exist within us.
They can be about saying no to certain things so that we may cultivate a richer relationship internally with ourselves.
Nourishing boundaries are about preserving our time and our energy to make space to reflect and to integrate our lived experiences.
They allow space for nothingness, for pause, for rest, for listening, for tuning in, for quiet.
.
.
Here in the west, our cultural environment can push us to fill every nook and cranny with busyness.
Our environment can guilt us for saying “I need to take some time for myself today” so we might say “I’m really busy” instead.
This isn’t about shaming the environment we live in.
It’s about noticing it and asking ourselves what parts we may need to tweak/adapt to better fit our preferred experience.
.
.
For some of us, our capacity might look radically different than other people’s capacity.
It’s important that we are sensitive and honoring towards our unique temperament.
It’s important that we are aware of context, and culture, so that we can see how those things are shaping and influencing us.
.
.
It may also be important to understand potential neurodivergent and/or mental and physical health differences.
It may be important to find ways to tend to any resistance or guilt we may experience around honoring our choices.
.
.
It may be important to reflect and discern when we may want to honor our current capacity versus when we might benefit from a tiny bit of stretching to honor a supportive kind of growth.
#coachingwithsilvy

node.text:
Becoming intimately familiar with our core vulnerabilities and the core vulnerabilities of our loved ones can be such a profound gift.
Being fully healed has become idealized in our modern times.
This idealization of reaching enlightened and perfectly healed states is nothing new, it has existed within many different contexts before - it has merely changed forms and is pointed toward the context of mental health currently.
.
.
That rush/pressure to heal things that are not necessary meant to be healed can do so much damage.
That pressure can sometimes cause us to secretly tuck our bruises away, even when those bruises are still very much alive and a part of our lived experience.
It can convince us to hide our very humanness, the parts of us that makes us so perfectly imperfect and yet so lovable.
It can also add a layer to shame to our painful experiences.
.
.
Here are some things that might help to make space to expand/soften the healing conversation:
.
.
✨Have the willingness to lovingly embrace that each person may have 2-3 core vulnerabilities (sometimes more) that will move through every stage of life with them. This isn’t something to get rid of, but something to be mindful and sensitive about.
.
.
✨Cultivate an awareness that having vulnerable areas does not (in any way) make someone flawed/broken or incapable of being in loving relationships.
.
.
✨Know that tending to your vulnerabilities is often both a personal and a relational experience.
.
.
✨Some vulnerabilities and fears are existential and innately human. There are some experiences that are not meant to be solved or overcome, they are meant to be held and embraced and tolerated.
.
.
✨We can tend to our healing and be in relationships with others simultaneously.
They are not necessarily mutually exclusive. Sometimes they are, but sometimes they are not.
#coachingwithsilvy

node.text:
People are generally more able to express their vulnerable experiences when they feel capable of regulating themselves.
They might reveal their tender parts more easily if they didn’t need to develop strong defenses to protect those tender parts.
They may present their sharings in more integrated ways when their earlier emotions and experiences were mirrored and validated and contained by their caregivers or safe relationships.
.
.
People can tend to relax/trust more easily in their adult relationships when they have a strong enough sense that their needs mattered as children.
There is a more developed sense of confidence to reach for and speak their needs when they have evidence that their reachings were previously responded to with warmth and care.
.
.
The very things that were left neglected, or were met with a lack of care or compassion, often find a way to surface in people’s adult relationships.
If someone needed more empathy from their caregivers, they might struggle to see or accept the empathy that is perhaps now being offered to them.
Or they may be drawn to partners or friends who struggle with offering empathy as a way to resolve and work through this part of their childhood.
.
.
If someone’s emotions were not contained or held well for them as children, they may find all sorts of reasons to lash out at their partners/friends as an unconscious cry for help.
.
.
In many ways, these things that may still be (unconscious to someone) need to be played out through these relational challenges.
Experiencing childhood woundings played out and projected externally is sometimes the only way someone we can begin to (see) them outside of themselves.
.
.
It can sometimes be the initial access point to help someone become aware of what is asking to be tended to and nurtured.
What someone chooses to do with that awareness and how willing or able they are to gently lean towards it, and learn to own it, is of course, a whole other story.
#coachingwithsilvy
.
.
How does this land for you?

node.text:
I wrote these words a few years ago.
It has been shared more than any other of my posts.
And while the words still ring true, if I were to write them again, I would word them a bit differently, in this way:
.
.
“Offering empathy to others without ever exploring our own needs, limits, and boundaries can sometimes cause us to become overwhelmed and burned out. While empathy in itself is an unlimited resource, the human extending it, isn’t. And tuning into our moment to moment capacity and honoring that space is a way of also empathizing with ourselves.”
.
.
It’s beautiful and vital to empathize, to attune, to listen, to care, to be present.
However, we can suffer immensely when our boundaries become so blurred that we can no longer tell whose feelings belong to who.
.
.
Noticing and being aware of this tendency to over-focus on others can be a great place to start.
Noticing when we are leaning too far into someone else’s lane long after our presence is wanted/required can be a great place to start.
Noticing parts of (ourselves) that may be seeking our own attention when we are busy trying to “focus” on another might be a great place to start.
.
.
Here’s an example:
Someone shares a deep and painful experience with you.
You spend a significant amount of time/energy helping them work though things.
When (they) have worked through the situation, (you) find yourself still feeling deeply affected by it.
.
.
You then find yourself feeling deeply resentful/frustrated that they have completely moved on from it, while you are still in the depths of it.
Sometimes this may be because you are feeling under-appreciated.
Sometimes this might be because you may strongly identify with caretaking others.
.
.
Whatever the reason, this can be a beautiful opportunity to strengthen your own emotional boundaries or to explore what might be activated within you.
.
.
Empathy without the self-awareness to create internal boundaries when necessary can be self-defeating.
Empathy with boundaries is an ongoing practice — one that can slowly enable us stay within with our own integrity as well as honor the integrity of others.
#coachingwithsilvy

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Silvy Khoucasian on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'One of the greatest privileges of a human being is to become midwife to the birth of the soul in another person. John O'Donohue'.

node.text:
One of the greatest privileges of my life has been being able to work alongside of and support my amazing clients; it has been to witness them take risks to bare their souls, to see them walk into the unknown and reveal the parts of themselves that feel unfamiliar, and tender, parts that have long been deemed as forbidden.
.
.
One of the other privileges of my life has been having access to coaches, therapists, and healers, (all of whom I consider wise and spiritual elders).
.
.
One of the sad tragedies of our time is that so many of us have lost access to communities, to healing and necessary rituals, to the wisdom and guidance from grounded and nurturing wise elders.
.
.
Having support to transition from one developmental stage to another calls for a village, it calls for a unique kind of witnessing.
It calls for an honoring and tending to the complexity and spectrum of emotions.
It calls for a recognition and validation of the joy and the (often neglected grief) that often yearns to come through upon taking these courageous transitional leaps.
.
.
If you are making a big transition in your life right now, (most of us are due to this pandemic), please know that you were never meant to go though these experiences alone.
You were never meant to cross over into your initiations alone, or with only one partner or friend.
Yes, parts of you are meant and may benefit from being discovered alone, but the integration process needs support.
.
.
Our souls come alive in the presence of other souls.
Our souls yearn to dance and grieve and play and struggle and not know in the presence of other souls.
Our souls long to birth themselves, again and again and again with other souls that have remembered and stepped into their own births.
.
.
The cost of being stripped away from our wise elders and communities is high.
Finding new ways to create this communal and supportive environment in our generation will be vital.
#coachingwithsilvy
